    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-25T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-25T03:00:00-05:00" n="790"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d790">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11275: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-25T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >November 25, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 25—8:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>565. Department’s 315, November 24, 6 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Although there have been newspaper reports that several of the Cabinet
                        councilors have been pressing the Prime Minister to take action toward
                        declaration of war, we can find no evidence or any substantial belief that
                        any decision has been taken in the sense suggested by Shanghai
                        informant.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>For our comment please see paragraph 2 of our 561, November 23, 3
                        p.m.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
